<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Grneyes</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hello Fellow Healers<P> I am really enjoying my new Greater Healing spell. My tanks love it since trying to heal a warrior with 750 to 900 hps using "Healing" was kind of rough on me. Now I can wait till they are at 75% before I start healing.<P> I normally team up with my friend Pippypie Fearless Gnome Warrior and were a good duo and really have alot of fun. We have been primarily in Pauldral Caverns getting insane XP.<P> Here is my situation. Much higher level players like to come along and drive by buff. This really makes Pippypie happy (+1200 HPs with the buff) but now I cannot heal her as efficiently as before. The only time it becomes a problem is when theres a bad pull and we have many adds. <BR> <BR> I also cannot buff her. My cleric buffs won't stick? I guess this is a stacking issue?<P>1: Ok so how do I deal with players Drive-By-Buffing my tank(s)? (I don't mind just need advice)<P>2: Where can I learn about buffs that do and don't stack?<P> Thank you for any and all replies.<P>Grneyes<BR>26 Healer of Brell<BR>Zeb server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Corish-MT</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Actually it doesn't matter how many HP your melee has, if you can't heal faster then they take damage.  There's zero difference in down-time between trying to heal a 1000 HP warrior, and a 2000 HP warrior (assuming you don't have complete heal).  If both are taking 500 HP of damage per minute, you need to heal 500 HP of damage per minute.  With either melee, you're going to run out of mana at the same time, at which point you have to stop and rest.<P>More HP on a melee just means you can fight for longer in a single fight before you have to start casting heals.  They still take the same amount of damage during that fight, you just have a larger "safety margin" before they fall over dead.  Since melees fight just as well at 40% health as at 100% health, more HP is just safety margin.<P>er, hopefully all that makes sense.<P>Now, where you may have an issue is when you are using the Courage-Bravery-Valor-etc as a heal (it's very efficient at around 2 HP per mana, and also a low-taunt heal).  None of the spells in that "Valor" line will stack, and you can't overwrite an upper level buff in that spell line with a lower level buff from the same spell line.<P>Hmm, mid-20s, you'll get Superior Healing soon, plus you have Celestial Remedy, and your "Valor" line is a very viable heal now.<P>Pop on over to: <A HREF="http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spells.asp?Class=Cleric" TARGET=_blank>http://eq.castersrealm.com/spells/spells.asp?Class=Cleric</A> <P>Basically we have (2) lines of HP and HP/AC buff spells:<P>Valor: courage-bravery-valor-resolution-etc.<BR>Symbols: pizarn, naltron, etcc.<P>You can't stack two spells from the same "line" on a single person.  Higher level spells from the same line will over-write lower-level spells, and lower-level spells won't stick if the higher level buff is already on that person.  Also, our valor line, conflicts with the druids "skin like" line.  You'll need to discuss it over with any druids from your mid-20s on as to whether you'll use the "valor" line, or their "skin like" line of spells on your groupmates.<P>------------------<BR>Corish, 46 Cleric of Morell-Thule</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Corish-MT</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hmmm, a few more things (you've got me thinking)...<P>Not sure if this is possible in your mid-20s, but ideally, a single-mob fight should only take 20% of your mana pool (maybe 30%).  I've found this to be true starting somewhere in my mid-30s, while the druids and wizards are constantly saying 20m, 30m after a fight, I'm saying 80m and the puller runs off and pulls another one.  My reason for saying a fight should leave you at 80% (which you can usually med back up before the next fight)?  60-70% of your mana bar is for emergency use only (picture 4 mobs suddenly showing up at camp, you're going to burn a lot of mana on crowd-control, healing people who got aggro until things get locked down and you can start medding again).  All of a sudden, you'll be looked at as "smart" for saving your mana for an emergency rather than nuking to speed up fights.<P>Maybe not possible in the late 20s, unless you have a solid main tank, and people are keeping aggro on the tank and not ping-ponging the mob.  It was just something that I thought of as I wondered if, since I was always at 80m, if I should start nuking.<P>-------<P>I also wanted to revisit my numbers on whether more HP means less efficient healing...<P>1000 HP tank<BR>500 dmg per fight from a mob<BR>1 minute per mob fight<BR>I regain 25% of my mana each minute<BR>I can heal 2000 HP if I'm at full mana.<P>In that scenario, I will never run out of mana because I med back 500 HP worth of healing power each minute (25% of 2000 HP) which I then heal the tank with because they took 500 HP worth of damage during that minute.<P>However, if the mobs suddenly start dealing 600 dmg per fight, and the pull rate is still once per minute.  I'm going to run out of mana after about 20 fights (I start with 2000 HP of healing power, but only have 1900 HP of healing power after the first minute because healing the melee took 30% of my mana, and I only med back 25% of my mana pool per minute, meaning that I'm losing 5% mana per minute fought).<P>Once I run dry (around 20 minutes), we have to stop and meditate for 4 minutes for me to med back to full.  And the only reason is that the mobs did more damage per minute then my meditating could keep up with.<P>------------------<BR>Corish, 46 Cleric of Morell-Thule</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">ejkas</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">As a cleric you have 3 main lines of spells<BR>1) First is the Courage line of spells. This is an hp/ac buff, and our most widely used buff. You cannot stack one hp/ac buff with another. In other words you cannot cast daring on someone with valor. In situations where you do attempt to cast a spell from this line on someone with an hp/ac buff 2 things can happen. If your spell is a higher level spell or is the same spell being cast from a higher level, your spell will overwrite the old hp/ac buff. If your spell (as in your situation with drive by buffs) is lower level than that on your target, you will get a message that your spell would not take hold. Don't worry about this... be grateful you don't lose mana anymore when this happens.<BR>Druids have a line of buffs that are also hp/ac, they are the ones that start Skin like _____ (wood, stone, steel, etc). Because of the nature of their buffs, this line of spells will not stack with the cleric courage line. If a higher level druid gives your friend Skin like Nature, you will be unable to cast bravery on him/her.<BR>Our spells in this line are: (lvl)<BR>Courage (1)<BR>Center (9)<BR>Daring (19)<BR>Bravery (24)<BR>Valor (34)<BR>Resolution (44)<BR>Heroism (52)<BR>Fortitude (55)<BR>Aegolism (60)<P>2) The second line of buffs we receive is a line of Armor class buffs. This is the line starting with Holy Armor. As with hp/ac buffs, ac buffs will not stack with other ac buffs. You cannot cast Spirit armor on a person with Shield of Words. You won't find too much conflict with other classes on this. Rangers are the only class I can think of that might interfere with this. Other buffs, shaman ones in particular, can buff stats that cause an increase in ac; the