kill more, get exp, and then you'll eventually get those buffs that are causing you trouble.<P><BR>Good Luck,<BR>Ejkas</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Grneyes</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hello<BR> Thank you for the very informative replies. I  guess I really showed my ignorance.<BR> <BR> Am I correct in thinking that I could just repeatedly cast Bravery on my tank which would be low aggro and also sort of a heal at the same time? Casting Bravery twice would restore 280 hps and 140 manna where as GH heals for 300 hps and costs me 150 manna? WOW I certainly wished I had known or figured this out sooner (if I am correct). <BR> <BR> Many times I would cast Celestial Remedy on Pippy when she brought adds just so that she would get the benefit of the spell and I wouldn't get knocked around. Eventually I would cast GH to keep her going but that normally meant that I was trying to root park one of the adds now so interested in me.<BR> <BR> I cannot wait to tell her what I learned. She tends to over protect me since she found without me around she doesn't last long.<BR> <BR> I have nearly broken Pippy of the habit of leaving her mob to come assist me. I think its easier just for her to concentrate on what she is doing and let me deal with whatever has taken an interest in me. Sometimes when root will work I park it. If she is close to finishing her MOB but I am taking massive damage (Bandits in PC can hit for up to 100) I will DA and hope 18 seconds is enough. Lastly I will melee which is not a good decision since even though my offensive and weapon skills are maxed I am very inefficient.<P> Again thank you very much and may your diety guide you<P>Grneyes<BR>26 Dwarven Cleric<BR>Zeb server<P>[This message has been edited by Grneyes (edited 04-10-2002).]<p>[This message has been edited by Grneyes (edited 04-10-2002).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kalef Bonemender</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">One thing that has not been blatantly stated is that with those higher lvl buffs(courage/skinlike and holy armor line) add ac.  With those higher lvl buffs, your tank may be getting an additional 20-50 ac beyond what you can suppply which is beneficial in her tanking ability.  Also if its skin like nature(sln) or higher, i believe they all have a small regen component to them(1 extra hp regen per tick i think it is).  The only disadvantage is if you were healing your tank with your own buffs.  Heheh i didnt know this when i was a young cleric either.<P>Kalef Bonemender<BR>56 Cleric<BR>Quellious</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Luminar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">first.. I cant see any buff that over writes yours being any worse for you. I think whats happening is your feeling inferior when your tank now has alot more hp due to a high level buff and visualy, your heal makes less of an impact. in reality how every our not healing any less hp then you did before.<P>second, useing buffs as heals. what most everyone seems to forget, and this actually only makes a difference after level 30, is you SAVE mana when you specialize in alteration. so when you get pretty high in your specialize, you use less mana than the spell calls for. (High levels can see this happen often when you have just whiped out and your medding up resurections.. you click JUST as you have enough mana to cast yet when your done casting, you still have a sliver of mana left.) this is also why buffing seems like it whipes your mana out faster.<P>------------------<BR>---<P><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=32524" TARGET=_blank>Magelo Profile</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">JanSorensen</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">At level 24 it will be something like this (note that spells dont do the full benifit at first you get them - and that we as clerics heal 5% more than listed for heals but not buffs)<P>Healing - 99 hp / 60 mana / 3.0 sec (1.65)<BR>CelRem - 295 hp / 190 mana / 28.0 sec (1.55)<BR>Bravery - 114 hp / 70 mana / 2.75 sec (1.63)<BR>GH - 302 hp / 150 mana / 3.75 sec (2.01)<P>Using Bravary as a heal has the added value that you never have to rebuff it  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"> I still remember having to teach druids in MM *not* to Skin people as I was using Bravery + GH as my heal spells.<P>------------------<BR><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4264" TARGET=_blank>Mikar of the Nexus</A><BR>High Priest of Brell<BR><A HREF="http://companions.windsofstorm.net/" TARGET=_blank>The Companions</A><BR>The Tribunal</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Corish-MT</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hmm, the numbers you gave for Bravery seem a bit off (maybe you gave the minimum amount of HP gained when you first get the spell at level 24?).  At full effect, Bravery is more like 140 hp (giving you a 2.00 ratio).<P>Healing - 99 hp / 60 mana / 3.0 sec (1.65)<BR>CelRem - 295 hp / 190 mana / 28.0 sec (1.55)<BR>Bravery - 140 hp / 70 mana / 2.75 sec (2.00)<BR>GH - 302 hp / 150 mana / 3.75 sec (2.01)<P>and to continue the trend, at level 34 you get:<P>Superior - 583 hp / 250 mana / 4.5 sec (2.332)<BR>Valor - 200 hp / 90 mana / 3.0 sec (2.22)<P>/em nods at Luminar<P>Specialization is really starting to kick in for me in my mid-late 40s.  That extra 15% you save (approximately, when it kicks in) usually means an extra heal somewhere in that full bar of mana.  Even so, I still use Resolution as a touch-up heal when I'm either looking to avoid aggro on a caster who's over-nuked (and isn't still getting beat on) because it's a fast cast or when I only need to heal about 250 hp.<P>/em waves at Grneyes<P>Yes, you can chain-cast bravery (it refreshes instantly, unlike a stun with a few second recast time).  Sooner or later you will gain aggro from it (or event CelRmdy) as it is only a low-taunt heal.  <P>If you want to go to "aggro-management boot camp" go get yourself into the High Keep Warrior Room group at level 26.  Just show up early in the prime time, and you'll be more likely either to help start the WR group or get on the list soon enough that you don't have to wait all day.  Nothing like 2-3 unmezzed goblins running around while you're trying to keep everyone alive and avoid aggro.  (My worst day in there was 5-6 deaths, and 3 were me dying.)  You'll learn the value of channeling, and healing with your back to a corner to avoid getting interrupted while casting.<P>Also a good place to play zergling healer (die after running out of mana, memorize your heal spells quick, jump back in naked with a full bar of mana).  You'll only have maybe 2/3 the mana that you have fully-geared, but it's 2/3 more mana then you had when you died.  Granted, playing zergling healer is not always popular with your groupmates and does a good bit of damage to your experience bar.  But in a pinch, it can keep deaths to a minimum when you get overrun.<P>------------------<BR>Corish, 46 Cleric of Morell-Thule</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tundar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I like to do drive by buffing.<BR>If you buff someone with "just" a 26 cleric the best thing you can do is casting an AC buff. This is will help the tank from taking more damage/getting hit.<BR>Don't forget, if your tank has 1200 hp and takes damage that puts him below 50% and you are LOM, you can easily tell him to dig out those bandaids and start getting that bind wounds skill up  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR>That won't be as safe if he only has 600hp.<P>I got Group Aego from a guildie when playing my L12 